143template<typename A, typename B>
144inline A reinterpret(const B &b) {
145 static_assert(sizeof(A) == sizeof(B), "type size mismatch");
146 A a;
147 memcpy(&a, &b, sizeof(a));

154template<typename T>
155inline int halide_popcount(T a) {
156 int bits_set = 0;
157 while (a != 0) {
158 bits_set += a & 1;
159 a >>= 1;
160 }
161 return bits_set;
162}
163
164template<typename T>
165inline int halide_count_leading_zeros(T a) {
166 int leading_zeros = 0;
167 int bit = sizeof(a) * 8 - 1;
168 while (bit >= 0 && (a & (((T)1) << bit)) == 0) {
169 leading_zeros++;
170 bit--;
171 }
172 return leading_zeros;
173}
174
175template<typename T>
176inline int halide_count_trailing_zeros(T a) {
177 int trailing_zeros = 0;
178 constexpr int bits = sizeof(a) * 8;
179 int bit = 0;
180 while (bit < bits && (a & (((T)1) << bit)) == 0) {
181 trailing_zeros++;
182 bit++;
183 }
184 return trailing_zeros;
185}

223class TypeInfoGatherer : public IRGraphVisitor {
224private:
225 using IRGraphVisitor::include;
226 using IRGraphVisitor::visit;
227
228 void include_type(const Type &t) {
229 if (t.is_vector()) {
230 if (t.is_bool()) {
231 // bool vectors are always emitted as uint8 in the C++ backend
232 // TODO: on some architectures, we could do better by choosing
233 // a bitwidth that matches the other vectors in use; EliminateBoolVectors
234 // could be used for this with a bit of work.
235 vector_types_used.insert(UInt(8).with_lanes(t.lanes()));
236 } else if (!t.is_handle()) {
237 // Vector-handle types can be seen when processing (e.g.)
238 // require() statements that are vectorized, but they
239 // will all be scalarized away prior to use, so don't emit
240 // them.
241 vector_types_used.insert(t);
242 if (t.is_int()) {
243 // If we are including an int-vector type, also include
244 // the same-width uint-vector type; there are various operations
245 // that can use uint vectors for intermediate results (e.g. lerp(),
246 // but also Mod, which can generate a call to abs() for int types,
247 // which always produces uint results for int inputs in Halide);
248 // it's easier to just err on the side of extra vectors we don't
249 // use since they are just type declarations.
250 vector_types_used.insert(t.with_code(halide_type_uint));
251 }
252 }
253 }
254 }
255
256 void include_lerp_types(const Type &t) {
257 if (t.is_vector() && t.is_int_or_uint() && (t.bits() >= 8 && t.bits() <= 32)) {
258 include_type(t.widen());
259 }
260 }
261
262protected:
263 void include(const Expr &e) override {
264 include_type(e.type());
265 IRGraphVisitor::include(e);
266 }
267
268 // GCC's __builtin_shuffle takes an integer vector of
269 // the size of its input vector. Make sure this type exists.
270 void visit(const Shuffle *op) override {
271 vector_types_used.insert(Int(32, op->vectors[0].type().lanes()));
272 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
273 }
274
275 void visit(const For *op) override {
276 for_types_used.insert(op->for_type);
277 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
278 }
279
280 void visit(const Ramp *op) override {
281 include_type(op->type.with_lanes(op->lanes));
282 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
283 }
284
285 void visit(const Broadcast *op) override {
286 include_type(op->type.with_lanes(op->lanes));
287 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
288 }
289
290 void visit(const Cast *op) override {
291 include_type(op->type);
292 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
293 }
294
295 void visit(const Call *op) override {
296 include_type(op->type);
297 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::lerp)) {
298 // lower_lerp() can synthesize wider vector types.
299 for (const auto &a : op->args) {
300 include_lerp_types(a.type());
301 }
302 } else if (op->is_intrinsic()) {
303 Expr lowered = lower_intrinsic(op);
304 if (lowered.defined()) {
305 lowered.accept(this);
306 return;
307 }
308 }
309
310 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
311 }
312
313public:
314 std::set<ForType> for_types_used;
315 std::set<Type> vector_types_used;
316};

320CodeGen_C::CodeGen_C(ostream &s, const Target &t, OutputKind output_kind, const std::string &guard)
321 : IRPrinter(s), id("$$ BAD ID $$"), target(t), output_kind(output_kind),
322 extern_c_open(false), inside_atomic_mutex_node(false), emit_atomic_stores(false), using_vector_typedefs(false) {
323
324 if (is_header()) {
325 // If it's a header, emit an include guard.
326 stream << "#ifndef HALIDE_" << c_print_name(guard) << "\n"
327 << "#define HALIDE_" << c_print_name(guard) << "\n"
328 << "#include <stdint.h>\n"
329 << "\n"
330 << "// Forward declarations of the types used in the interface\n"
331 << "// to the Halide pipeline.\n"
332 << "//\n";
333 if (target.has_feature(Target::NoRuntime)) {
334 stream << "// For the definitions of these structs, include HalideRuntime.h\n";
335 } else {
336 stream << "// Definitions for these structs are below.\n";
337 }
338 stream << "\n"
339 << "// Halide's representation of a multi-dimensional array.\n"
340 << "// Halide::Runtime::Buffer is a more user-friendly wrapper\n"
341 << "// around this. Its declaration is in HalideBuffer.h\n"
342 << "struct halide_buffer_t;\n"
343 << "\n"
344 << "// Metadata describing the arguments to the generated function.\n"
345 << "// Used to construct calls to the _argv version of the function.\n"
346 << "struct halide_filter_metadata_t;\n"
347 << "\n";
348 // We just forward declared the following types:
349 forward_declared.insert(type_of<halide_buffer_t *>().handle_type);
350 forward_declared.insert(type_of<halide_filter_metadata_t *>().handle_type);
351 } else if (is_extern_decl()) {
352 // Extern decls to be wrapped inside other code (eg python extensions);
353 // emit the forward decls with a minimum of noise. Note that we never
354 // mess with legacy buffer types in this case.
355 stream << "struct halide_buffer_t;\n"
356 << "struct halide_filter_metadata_t;\n"
357 << "\n";
358 forward_declared.insert(type_of<halide_buffer_t *>().handle_type);
359 forward_declared.insert(type_of<halide_filter_metadata_t *>().handle_type);
360 } else {
361 // Include declarations of everything generated C source might want
362 stream
363 << headers
364 << globals
365 << halide_internal_runtime_header_HalideRuntime_h << "\n"
366 << halide_internal_initmod_inlined_c << "\n";
367 stream << "\n";
368 }
369
370 stream << kDefineMustUseResult << "\n";
371
372 // Throw in a default (empty) definition of HALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS
373 // (some hosts may define this to e.g. __attribute__((warn_unused_result)))
374 stream << "#ifndef HALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS\n";
375 stream << "#define HALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS\n";
376 stream << "#endif\n";
377}

379CodeGen_C::~CodeGen_C() {
380 set_name_mangling_mode(NameMangling::Default);
381
382 if (is_header()) {
383 if (!target.has_feature(Target::NoRuntime)) {
384 stream << "\n"
385 << "// The generated object file that goes with this header\n"
386 << "// includes a full copy of the Halide runtime so that it\n"
387 << "// can be used standalone. Declarations for the functions\n"
388 << "// in the Halide runtime are below.\n";
389 if (target.os == Target::Windows) {
390 stream
391 << "//\n"
392 << "// The inclusion of this runtime means that it is not legal\n"
393 << "// to link multiple Halide-generated object files together.\n"
394 << "// This problem is Windows-specific. On other platforms, we\n"
395 << "// use weak linkage.\n";
396 } else {
397 stream
398 << "//\n"
399 << "// The runtime is defined using weak linkage, so it is legal\n"
400 << "// to link multiple Halide-generated object files together,\n"
401 << "// or to clobber any of these functions with your own\n"
402 << "// definition.\n";
403 }
404 stream << "//\n"
405 << "// To generate an object file without a full copy of the\n"
406 << "// runtime, use the -no_runtime target flag. To generate a\n"
407 << "// standalone Halide runtime to use with such object files\n"
408 << "// use the -r flag with any Halide generator binary, e.g.:\n"
409 << "// $ ./my_generator -r halide_runtime -o . target=host\n"
410 << "\n"
411 << halide_internal_runtime_header_HalideRuntime_h << "\n";
412 if (target.has_feature(Target::CUDA)) {
413 stream << halide_internal_runtime_header_HalideRuntimeCuda_h << "\n";
414 }
415 if (target.has_feature(Target::HVX)) {
416 stream << halide_internal_runtime_header_HalideRuntimeHexagonHost_h << "\n";
417 }
418 if (target.has_feature(Target::Metal)) {
419 stream << halide_internal_runtime_header_HalideRuntimeMetal_h << "\n";
420 }
421 if (target.has_feature(Target::OpenCL)) {
422 stream << halide_internal_runtime_header_HalideRuntimeOpenCL_h << "\n";
423 }
424 if (target.has_feature(Target::OpenGLCompute)) {

450// We can't use std::array because that has its own overload of operator<, etc,
451// which will interfere with ours.
452template <typename ElementType, size_t Lanes>
453struct CppVector {
454 ElementType elements[Lanes];
455
456 HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE
457 ElementType& operator[](size_t i) {
458 return elements[i];
459 }
460
461 HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE
462 const ElementType operator[](size_t i) const {
463 return elements[i];
464 }
465
466 HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE
467 ElementType *data() {
468 return elements;
469 }
470
471 HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE
472 const ElementType *data() const {
473 return elements;
474 }
475};
476
477template <typename ElementType_, size_t Lanes_>
478class CppVectorOps {
479public:
480 using ElementType = ElementType_ ;
481 static constexpr size_t Lanes = Lanes_;
482
483 using Vec = CppVector<ElementType, Lanes>;
484 using Mask = CppVector<uint8_t, Lanes>;
485
486 CppVectorOps() = delete;
487
488 static Vec broadcast(const ElementType v) {
489 Vec r;
490 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
491 r[i] = v;
492 }
493 return r;
494 }
495
496 static Vec ramp(const ElementType base, const ElementType stride) {
497 Vec r;
498 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
499 r[i] = base + stride * i;
500 }
501 return r;
502 }
503
504 static Vec load(const void *base, int32_t offset) {
505 Vec r;
506 memcpy(r.data(), ((const ElementType*)base + offset), sizeof(ElementType) * Lanes);
507 return r;
508 }
509
510 static Vec load_gather(const void *base, const CppVector<int32_t, Lanes> &offset) {
511 Vec r;
512 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
513 r[i] = ((const ElementType*)base)[offset[i]];
514 }
515 return r;
516 }
517
518 static Vec load_predicated(const void *base, const CppVector<int32_t, Lanes> &offset, const Mask &predicate) {
519 Vec r;
520 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
521 if (predicate[i]) {
522 r[i] = ((const ElementType*)base)[offset[i]];
523 }
524 }
525 return r;
526 }
527
528 static void store(const Vec &v, void *base, int32_t offset) {
529 memcpy(((ElementType*)base + offset), v.data(), sizeof(ElementType) * Lanes);
530 }
531
532 static void store_scatter(const Vec &v, void *base, const CppVector<int32_t, Lanes> &offset) {
533 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
534 ((ElementType*)base)[offset[i]] = v[i];
535 }
536 }
537
538 static void store_predicated(const Vec &v, void *base, const CppVector<int32_t, Lanes> &offset, const Mask &predicate) {
539 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
540 if (predicate[i]) {
541 ((ElementType*)base)[offset[i]] = v[i];
542 }
543 }
544 }

546 template<int... Indices>
547 static Vec shuffle(const Vec &a) {
548 static_assert(sizeof...(Indices) == Lanes, "shuffle() requires an exact match of lanes");
549 Vec r = { a[Indices]... };
550 return r;
551 }
552
553 static Vec replace(const Vec &v, size_t i, const ElementType b) {
554 Vec r = v;
555 r[i] = b;
556 return r;
557 }

561 Vec r;
562 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
563 r[i] = static_cast<ElementType>(src[i]);
564 }
565 return r;
566 }

584 static Vec select(const Mask &cond, const Vec &true_value, const Vec &false_value) {
585 Vec r;
586 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
587 r[i] = cond[i] ? true_value[i] : false_value[i];

589 return r;
590 }

592 static Mask logical_or(const Vec &a, const Vec &b) {

594 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
595 r[i] = a[i] || b[i] ? 0xff : 0x00;
596 }
597 return r;
598 }

603 r[i] = a[i] && b[i] ? 0xff : 0x00;

605 return r;

648 static Mask ne(const Vec &a, const Vec &b) {

1002template <typename ElementType_, size_t Lanes_>
1003class NativeVectorOps {
1004public:
1005 using ElementType = ElementType_ ;
1006 static constexpr size_t Lanes = Lanes_;
1007
1008 using Vec = NativeVector<ElementType, Lanes>;
1009 using Mask = NativeVector<uint8_t, Lanes>;
1010
1011 NativeVectorOps() = delete;
1012
1013 static Vec broadcast(const ElementType v) {
1014 const Vec zero = {}; // Zero-initialized native vector.
1015 return v - zero;
1016 }
1017
1018 static Vec ramp(const ElementType base, const ElementType stride) {
1019 Vec r;
1020 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1021 r[i] = base + stride * i;
1022 }
1023 return r;
1024 }
1025
1026 static Vec load(const void *base, int32_t offset) {
1027 Vec r;
1028 // We only require Vec to be element-aligned, so we can't safely just read
1029 // directly from memory (might segfault). Use memcpy for safety.
1030 //
1031 // If Vec is a non-power-of-two (e.g. uint8x48), the actual implementation
1032 // might be larger (e.g. it might really be a uint8x64). Only copy the amount
1033 // that is in the logical type, to avoid possible overreads.
1034 memcpy(&r, ((const ElementType*)base + offset), sizeof(ElementType) * Lanes);
1035 return r;
1036 }
1037
1038 static Vec load_gather(const void *base, const NativeVector<int32_t, Lanes> offset) {
1039 Vec r;
1040 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1041 r[i] = ((const ElementType*)base)[offset[i]];
1042 }
1043 return r;
1044 }
1045
1046 static Vec load_predicated(const void *base, const NativeVector<int32_t, Lanes> offset, const NativeVector<uint8_t, Lanes> predicate) {
1047 Vec r;
1048 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1049 if (predicate[i]) {
1050 r[i] = ((const ElementType*)base)[offset[i]];
1051 }
1052 }
1053 return r;
1054 }
1055 static void store(const Vec v, void *base, int32_t offset) {
1056 // We only require Vec to be element-aligned, so we can't safely just write
1057 // directly from memory (might segfault). Use memcpy for safety.
1058 //
1059 // If Vec is a non-power-of-two (e.g. uint8x48), the actual implementation
1060 // might be larger (e.g. it might really be a uint8x64). Only copy the amount
1061 // that is in the logical type, to avoid possible overreads.
1062 memcpy(((ElementType*)base + offset), &v, sizeof(ElementType) * Lanes);
1063 }
1064
1065 static void store_scatter(const Vec v, void *base, const NativeVector<int32_t, Lanes> offset) {
1066 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1067 ((ElementType*)base)[offset[i]] = v[i];
1068 }
1069 }
1070
1071 static void store_predicated(const Vec v, void *base, const NativeVector<int32_t, Lanes> offset, const NativeVector<uint8_t, Lanes> predicate) {
1072 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1073 if (predicate[i]) {
1074 ((ElementType*)base)[offset[i]] = v[i];
1075 }
1076 }
1077 }

1079 template<int... Indices>
1080 static Vec shuffle(const Vec a) {
1081 static_assert(sizeof...(Indices) == Lanes, "shuffle() requires an exact match of lanes");
1082#if __has_builtin(__builtin_shufflevector)
1083 // Clang
1084 return __builtin_shufflevector(a, a, Indices...);
1085#elif __has_builtin(__builtin_shuffle) || defined(__GNUC__)
1086 // GCC
1087 return __builtin_shuffle(a, NativeVector<int, sizeof...(Indices)>{Indices...});
1088#else
1089 Vec r = { a[Indices]... };
1090 return r;
1091#endif

1095 v[i] = b;
1096 return v;

1099 template <typename OtherVec>
1100 static Vec convert_from(const OtherVec src) {
1101#if __has_builtin(__builtin_convertvector)
1102 // Don't use __builtin_convertvector for float->int: it appears to have
1103 // different float->int rounding behavior in at least some situations;
1104 // for now we'll use the much-slower-but-correct explicit C++ code.
1105 // (https://github.com/halide/Halide/issues/2080)
1106 constexpr bool is_float_to_int = std::is_floating_point<OtherVec>::value &&
1107 std::is_integral<Vec>::value;
1108 if (!is_float_to_int) {
1109 return __builtin_convertvector(src, Vec);
1110 }
1111#endif
1112 // Fallthru for float->int, or degenerate compilers that support native vectors
1113 // but not __builtin_convertvector (Intel?)
1114 Vec r;
1115 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1116 r[i] = static_cast<ElementType>(src[i]);
1117 }
1118 return r;
1119 }

1121 static Vec max(const Vec a, const Vec b) {
1122#if defined(__GNUC__) && !defined(__clang__)
1123 // TODO: GCC doesn't seem to recognize this pattern, and scalarizes instead
1124 return a > b ? a : b;
1125#else
1126 // Clang doesn't do ternary operator for vectors, but recognizes this pattern
1127 Vec r;
1128 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1129 r[i] = a[i] > b[i] ? a[i] : b[i];
1130 }
1131 return r;
1132#endif
1133 }

1135 static Vec min(const Vec a, const Vec b) {
1136#if defined(__GNUC__) && !defined(__clang__)
1137 // TODO: GCC doesn't seem to recognize this pattern, and scalarizes instead
1138 return a < b ? a : b;
1139#else
1140 // Clang doesn't do ternary operator for vectors, but recognizes this pattern
1141 Vec r;
1142 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1143 r[i] = a[i] < b[i] ? a[i] : b[i];
1144 }
1145 return r;
1146#endif
1147 }

1149 static Vec select(const Mask cond, const Vec true_value, const Vec false_value) {
1150#if defined(__GNUC__) && !defined(__clang__)
1151 // This should do the correct lane-wise select.
1152 using T = typename NativeVectorComparisonType<ElementType>::type;
1153 auto b = NativeVectorOps<T, Lanes>::convert_from(cond);
1154 return b ? true_value : false_value;
1155#else
1156 // Clang doesn't do ternary operator for vectors, but recognizes this pattern
1157 Vec r;
1158 for (size_t i = 0; i < Lanes; i++) {
1159 r[i] = cond[i] ? true_value[i] : false_value[i];
1160 }
1161 return r;
1162#endif
1163 }

1254 string name = print_type(t, DoNotAppendSpace);
1255 string scalar_name = print_type(t.element_of(), DoNotAppendSpace);
1256 stream << "#if halide_cpp_use_native_vector(" << scalar_name << ", " << t.lanes() << ")\n";
1257 stream << "using " << name << " = NativeVector<" << scalar_name << ", " << t.lanes() << ">;\n";
1258 stream << "using " << name << "_ops = NativeVectorOps<" << scalar_name << ", " << t.lanes() << ">;\n";
1259 // Useful for debugging which Vector implementation is being selected
1260 // stream << "#pragma message \"using NativeVector for " << t << "\"\n";
1261 stream << "#else\n";
1262 stream << "using " << name << " = CppVector<" << scalar_name << ", " << t.lanes() << ">;\n";
1263 stream << "using " << name << "_ops = CppVectorOps<" << scalar_name << ", " << t.lanes() << ">;\n";
1264 // Useful for debugging which Vector implementation is being selected
1265 // stream << "#pragma message \"using CppVector for " << t << "\"\n";
1266 stream << "#endif\n";
1267 }
1268 }
1269
1270 using_vector_typedefs = true;
1271}
1272
1273void CodeGen_C::set_name_mangling_mode(NameMangling mode) {
1274 if (extern_c_open && mode != NameMangling::C) {
1275 stream << "\n#ifdef __cplusplus\n";
1276 stream << "} // extern \"C\"\n";
1277 stream << "#endif\n\n";
1278 extern_c_open = false;
1279 } else if (!extern_c_open && mode == NameMangling::C) {
1280 stream << "\n#ifdef __cplusplus\n";
1281 stream << "extern \"C\" {\n";
1282 stream << "#endif\n\n";
1283 extern_c_open = true;
1284 }
1285}

1287string CodeGen_C::print_type(Type type, AppendSpaceIfNeeded space_option) {
1288 return type_to_c_type(type, space_option == AppendSpace);
1289}
1290
1291string CodeGen_C::print_reinterpret(Type type, const Expr &e) {
1292 ostringstream oss;
1293 if (type.is_handle() || e.type().is_handle()) {
1294 // Use a c-style cast if either src or dest is a handle --
1295 // note that although Halide declares a "Handle" to always be 64 bits,
1296 // the source "handle" might actually be a 32-bit pointer (from
1297 // a function parameter), so calling reinterpret<> (which just memcpy's)
1298 // would be garbage-producing.
1299 oss << "(" << print_type(type) << ")";
1300 } else {
1301 oss << "reinterpret<" << print_type(type) << ">";
1302 }
1303 oss << "(" << print_expr(e) << ")";
1304 return oss.str();
1305}

1311namespace {
1312class ExternCallPrototypes : public IRGraphVisitor {
1313 struct NamespaceOrCall {
1314 const Call *call; // nullptr if this is a subnamespace
1315 std::map<string, NamespaceOrCall> names;
1316 NamespaceOrCall(const Call *call = nullptr)
1317 : call(call) {
1318 }
1319 };
1320 std::map<string, NamespaceOrCall> c_plus_plus_externs;
1321 std::map<string, const Call *> c_externs;
1322 std::set<std::string> processed;
1323 std::set<std::string> internal_linkage;
1324 std::set<std::string> destructors;
1325
1326 using IRGraphVisitor::visit;
1327
1328 void visit(const Call *op) override {
1329 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
1330
1331 if (!processed.count(op->name)) {
1332 if (op->call_type == Call::Extern || op->call_type == Call::PureExtern) {
1333 c_externs.insert({op->name, op});
1334 } else if (op->call_type == Call::ExternCPlusPlus) {
1335 std::vector<std::string> namespaces;
1336 std::string name = extract_namespaces(op->name, namespaces);
1337 std::map<string, NamespaceOrCall> *namespace_map = &c_plus_plus_externs;
1338 for (const auto &ns : namespaces) {
1339 auto insertion = namespace_map->insert({ns, NamespaceOrCall()});
1340 namespace_map = &insertion.first->second.names;
1341 }
1342 namespace_map->insert({name, NamespaceOrCall(op)});
1343 }
1344 processed.insert(op->name);
1345 }
1346
1347 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::register_destructor)) {
1348 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
1349 const StringImm *fn = op->args[0].as<StringImm>();
1350 internal_assert(fn);
1351 destructors.insert(fn->value);
1352 }
1353 }
1354
1355 void visit(const Allocate *op) override {
1356 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
1357 if (!op->free_function.empty()) {
1358 destructors.insert(op->free_function);
1359 }
1360 }
1361
1362 void emit_function_decl(ostream &stream, const Call *op, const std::string &name) const {
1363 // op->name (rather than the name arg) since we need the fully-qualified C++ name
1364 if (internal_linkage.count(op->name)) {
1365 stream << "static ";
1366 }
1367 stream << type_to_c_type(op->type, /* append_space */ true) << name << "(";
1368 if (function_takes_user_context(name)) {
1369 stream << "void *";
1370 if (!op->args.empty()) {
1371 stream << ", ";
1372 }
1373 }
1374 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
1375 if (i > 0) {
1376 stream << ", ";
1377 }
1378 if (op->args[i].as<StringImm>()) {
1379 stream << "const char *";
1380 } else {
1381 stream << type_to_c_type(op->args[i].type(), true);
1382 }
1383 }
1384 stream << ");\n";
1385 }
1386
1387 void emit_namespace_or_call(ostream &stream, const NamespaceOrCall &ns_or_call, const std::string &name) const {
1388 if (ns_or_call.call == nullptr) {
1389 stream << "namespace " << name << " {\n";
1390 for (const auto &ns_or_call_inner : ns_or_call.names) {
1391 emit_namespace_or_call(stream, ns_or_call_inner.second, ns_or_call_inner.first);
1392 }
1393 stream << "} // namespace " << name << "\n";
1394 } else {
1395 emit_function_decl(stream, ns_or_call.call, name);
1396 }
1397 }
1398
1399public:
1400 ExternCallPrototypes() {
1401 // Make sure we don't catch calls that are already in the global declarations
1402 const char *strs[] = {globals.c_str(),
1403 (const char *)halide_internal_runtime_header_HalideRuntime_h,
1404 (const char *)halide_internal_initmod_inlined_c};
1405 for (const char *str : strs) {
1406 size_t j = 0;
1407 for (size_t i = 0; str[i]; i++) {
1408 char c = str[i];
1409 if (c == '(' && i > j + 1) {
1410 // Could be the end of a function_name.
1411 string name(str + j + 1, i - j - 1);
1412 processed.insert(name);
1413 }
1414
1415 if (('A' <= c && c <= 'Z') ||
1416 ('a' <= c && c <= 'z') ||
1417 c == '_' ||
1418 ('0' <= c && c <= '9')) {
1419 // Could be part of a function name.
1420 } else {
1421 j = i;
1422 }
1423 }
1424 }
1425 }
1426
1427 void set_internal_linkage(const std::string &name) {
1428 internal_linkage.insert(name);
1429 }
1430
1431 bool has_c_declarations() const {
1432 return !c_externs.empty();
1433 }
1434
1435 bool has_c_plus_plus_declarations() const {
1436 return !c_plus_plus_externs.empty();
1437 }
1438
1439 void emit_c_declarations(ostream &stream) const {
1440 for (const auto &call : c_externs) {
1441 emit_function_decl(stream, call.second, call.first);
1442 }
1443 for (const auto &d : destructors) {
1444 stream << "void " << d << "(void *, void *);\n";
1445 }
1446 stream << "\n";
1447 }
1448
1449 void emit_c_plus_plus_declarations(ostream &stream) const {
1450 for (const auto &ns_or_call : c_plus_plus_externs) {
1451 emit_namespace_or_call(stream, ns_or_call.second, ns_or_call.first);
1452 }
1453 stream << "\n";
1454 }
1455};
1456} // namespace
1457
1458void CodeGen_C::forward_declare_type_if_needed(const Type &t) {
1459 if (!t.handle_type ||
1460 forward_declared.count(t.handle_type) ||
1461 t.handle_type->inner_name.cpp_type_type == halide_cplusplus_type_name::Simple) {
1462 return;
1463 }
1464 for (const auto &ns : t.handle_type->namespaces) {
1465 stream << "namespace " << ns << " { ";
1466 }
1467 switch (t.handle_type->inner_name.cpp_type_type) {
1468 case halide_cplusplus_type_name::Simple:
1469 // nothing
1470 break;
1471 case halide_cplusplus_type_name::Struct:
1472 stream << "struct " << t.handle_type->inner_name.name << ";";
1473 break;
1474 case halide_cplusplus_type_name::Class:
1475 stream << "class " << t.handle_type->inner_name.name << ";";
1476 break;
1477 case halide_cplusplus_type_name::Union:
1478 stream << "union " << t.handle_type->inner_name.name << ";";
1479 break;
1480 case halide_cplusplus_type_name::Enum:
1481 internal_error << "Passing pointers to enums is unsupported\n";
1482 break;
1483 }
1484 for (const auto &ns : t.handle_type->namespaces) {
1485 (void)ns;
1486 stream << " }";
1487 }
1488 stream << "\n";
1489 forward_declared.insert(t.handle_type);
1490}
1491
1492void CodeGen_C::compile(const Module &input) {
1493 TypeInfoGatherer type_info;
1494 for (const auto &f : input.functions()) {
1495 if (f.body.defined()) {
1496 f.body.accept(&type_info);
1497 }
1498 }
1499 uses_gpu_for_loops = (type_info.for_types_used.count(ForType::GPUBlock) ||
1500 type_info.for_types_used.count(ForType::GPUThread) ||
1501 type_info.for_types_used.count(ForType::GPULane));
1502
1503 // Forward-declare all the types we need; this needs to happen before
1504 // we emit function prototypes, since those may need the types.
1505 stream << "\n";
1506 for (const auto &f : input.functions()) {
1507 for (const auto &arg : f.args) {
1508 forward_declare_type_if_needed(arg.type);
1509 }
1510 }
1511 stream << "\n";
1512
1513 if (!is_header_or_extern_decl()) {
1514 // Emit any external-code blobs that are C++.
1515 for (const ExternalCode &code_blob : input.external_code()) {
1516 if (code_blob.is_c_plus_plus_source()) {
1517 stream << "\n";
1518 stream << "// Begin External Code: " << code_blob.name() << "\n";
1519 stream.write((const char *)code_blob.contents().data(), code_blob.contents().size());
1520 stream << "\n";
1521 stream << "// End External Code: " << code_blob.name() << "\n";
1522 stream << "\n";
1523 }
1524 }
1525
1526 add_vector_typedefs(type_info.vector_types_used);
1527
1528 // Emit prototypes for all external and internal-only functions.
1529 // Gather them up and do them all up front, to reduce duplicates,
1530 // and to make it simpler to get internal-linkage functions correct.
1531 ExternCallPrototypes e;
1532 for (const auto &f : input.functions()) {
1533 f.body.accept(&e);
1534 if (f.linkage == LinkageType::Internal) {
1535 // We can't tell at the call site if a LoweredFunc is intended to be internal
1536 // or not, so mark them explicitly.
1537 e.set_internal_linkage(f.name);
1538 }
1539 }
1540
1541 if (e.has_c_plus_plus_declarations()) {
1542 set_name_mangling_mode(NameMangling::CPlusPlus);
1543 e.emit_c_plus_plus_declarations(stream);
1544 }
1545
1546 if (e.has_c_declarations()) {
1547 set_name_mangling_mode(NameMangling::C);
1548 e.emit_c_declarations(stream);
1549 }
1550 }
1551
1552 for (const auto &b : input.buffers()) {
1553 compile(b);
1554 }
1555 for (const auto &f : input.functions()) {
1556 compile(f);
1557 }
1558}
1559
1560void CodeGen_C::compile(const LoweredFunc &f) {
1561 // Don't put non-external function declarations in headers.
1562 if (is_header_or_extern_decl() && f.linkage == LinkageType::Internal) {
1563 return;
1564 }
1565
1566 const std::vector<LoweredArgument> &args = f.args;
1567
1568 have_user_context = false;
1569 for (size_t i = 0; i < args.size(); i++) {
1570 // TODO: check that its type is void *?
1571 have_user_context |= (args[i].name == "__user_context");
1572 }
1573
1574 NameMangling name_mangling = f.name_mangling;
1575 if (name_mangling == NameMangling::Default) {
1576 name_mangling = (target.has_feature(Target::CPlusPlusMangling) ? NameMangling::CPlusPlus : NameMangling::C);
1577 }
1578
1579 set_name_mangling_mode(name_mangling);
1580
1581 std::vector<std::string> namespaces;
1582 std::string simple_name = extract_namespaces(f.name, namespaces);
1583 if (!is_c_plus_plus_interface()) {
1584 user_assert(namespaces.empty()) << "Namespace qualifiers not allowed on function name if not compiling with Target::CPlusPlusNameMangling.\n";
1585 }
1586
1587 if (!namespaces.empty()) {
1588 for (const auto &ns : namespaces) {
1589 stream << "namespace " << ns << " {\n";
1590 }
1591 stream << "\n";
1592 }
1593
1594 // Emit the function prototype
1595 if (f.linkage == LinkageType::Internal) {
1596 // If the function isn't public, mark it static.
1597 stream << "static ";
1598 }
1599 stream << "HALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS\n";
1600 stream << "int " << simple_name << "(";
1601 for (size_t i = 0; i < args.size(); i++) {
1602 if (args[i].is_buffer()) {
1603 stream << "struct halide_buffer_t *"
1604 << print_name(args[i].name)
1605 << "_buffer";
1606 } else {
1607 stream << print_type(args[i].type, AppendSpace)
1608 << print_name(args[i].name);
1609 }
1610
1611 if (i < args.size() - 1) {
1612 stream << ", ";
1613 }
1614 }
1615
1616 if (is_header_or_extern_decl()) {
1617 stream << ");\n";
1618 } else {
1619 stream << ") {\n";
1620 indent += 1;
1621
1622 if (uses_gpu_for_loops) {
1623 stream << get_indent() << "halide_error("
1624 << (have_user_context ? "const_cast<void *>(__user_context)" : "nullptr")
1625 << ", \"C++ Backend does not support gpu_blocks() or gpu_threads() yet, "
1626 << "this function will always fail at runtime\");\n";
1627 stream << get_indent() << "return halide_error_code_device_malloc_failed;\n";
1628 } else {
1629 // Emit a local user_context we can pass in all cases, either
1630 // aliasing __user_context or nullptr.
1631 stream << get_indent() << "void * const _ucon = "
1632 << (have_user_context ? "const_cast<void *>(__user_context)" : "nullptr")
1633 << ";\n";
1634
1635 if (target.has_feature(Target::NoAsserts)) {
1636 stream << get_indent() << "halide_unused(_ucon);";
1637 }
1638
1639 // Emit the body
1640 print(f.body);
1641
1642 // Return success.
1643 stream << get_indent() << "return 0;\n";
1644 }
1645
1646 indent -= 1;
1647 stream << "}\n";
1648 }
1649
1650 if (is_header_or_extern_decl() && f.linkage == LinkageType::ExternalPlusMetadata) {
1651 // Emit the argv version
1652 stream << "\nHALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS\nint " << simple_name << "_argv(void **args);\n";
1653
1654 // And also the metadata.
1655 stream << "\nHALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS\nconst struct halide_filter_metadata_t *" << simple_name << "_metadata();\n";
1656 }
1657
1658 if (!namespaces.empty()) {
1659 stream << "\n";
1660 for (size_t i = namespaces.size(); i > 0; i--) {
1661 stream << "} // namespace " << namespaces[i - 1] << "\n";
1662 }
1663 stream << "\n";
1664 }
1665}
1666
1667void CodeGen_C::compile(const Buffer<> &buffer) {
1668 // Don't define buffers in headers or extern decls.
1669 if (is_header_or_extern_decl()) {
1670 return;
1671 }
1672
1673 string name = print_name(buffer.name());
1674 halide_buffer_t b = *(buffer.raw_buffer());
1675
1676 user_assert(b.host) << "Can't embed image: " << buffer.name() << " because it has a null host pointer\n";
1677 user_assert(!b.device_dirty()) << "Can't embed image: " << buffer.name() << "because it has a dirty device pointer\n";
1678
1679 // Figure out the offset of the last pixel.
1680 size_t num_elems = 1;
1681 for (int d = 0; d < b.dimensions; d++) {
1682 num_elems += b.dim[d].stride * (size_t)(b.dim[d].extent - 1);
1683 }
1684
1685 // For now, we assume buffers that aren't scalar are constant,
1686 // while scalars can be mutated. This accommodates all our existing
1687 // use cases, which is that all buffers are constant, except those
1688 // used to store stateful module information in offloading runtimes.
1689 bool is_constant = buffer.dimensions() != 0;
1690
1691 // If it is an GPU source kernel, we would like to see the actual output, not the
1692 // uint8 representation. We use a string literal for this.
1693 if (ends_with(name, "gpu_source_kernels")) {
1694 stream << "static const char *" << name << "_string = R\"BUFCHARSOURCE(";
1695 stream.write((char *)b.host, num_elems);
1696 stream << ")BUFCHARSOURCE\";\n";
1697
1698 stream << "static const uint8_t *" << name << "_data HALIDE_ATTRIBUTE_ALIGN(32) = (const uint8_t *) "
1699 << name << "_string;\n";
1700 } else {
1701 // Emit the data
1702 stream << "static " << (is_constant ? "const" : "") << " uint8_t " << name << "_data[] HALIDE_ATTRIBUTE_ALIGN(32) = {\n";
1703 stream << get_indent();
1704 for (size_t i = 0; i < num_elems * b.type.bytes(); i++) {
1705 if (i > 0) {
1706 stream << ",";
1707 if (i % 16 == 0) {
1708 stream << "\n";
1709 stream << get_indent();
1710 } else {
1711 stream << " ";
1712 }
1713 }
1714 stream << (int)(b.host[i]);
1715 }
1716 stream << "\n};\n";
1717 }
1718
1719 // Emit the shape (constant even for scalar buffers)
1720 stream << "static const halide_dimension_t " << name << "_buffer_shape[] = {";
1721 for (int i = 0; i < buffer.dimensions(); i++) {
1722 stream << "halide_dimension_t(" << buffer.dim(i).min()
1723 << ", " << buffer.dim(i).extent()
1724 << ", " << buffer.dim(i).stride() << ")";
1725 if (i < buffer.dimensions() - 1) {
1726 stream << ", ";
1727 }
1728 }
1729 stream << "};\n";
1730
1731 Type t = buffer.type();
1732
1733 // Emit the buffer struct. Note that although our shape and (usually) our host
1734 // data is const, the buffer itself isn't: embedded buffers in one pipeline
1735 // can be passed to another pipeline (e.g. for an extern stage), in which
1736 // case the buffer objects need to be non-const, because the constness
1737 // (from the POV of the extern stage) is a runtime property.
1738 stream << "static halide_buffer_t " << name << "_buffer_ = {"
1739 << "0, " // device
1740 << "nullptr, " // device_interface
1741 << "const_cast<uint8_t*>(&" << name << "_data[0]), " // host
1742 << "0, " // flags
1743 << "halide_type_t((halide_type_code_t)(" << (int)t.code() << "), " << t.bits() << ", " << t.lanes() << "), "
1744 << buffer.dimensions() << ", "
1745 << "const_cast<halide_dimension_t*>(" << name << "_buffer_shape)};\n";
1746
1747 // Make a global pointer to it.
1748 stream << "static halide_buffer_t * const " << name << "_buffer = &" << name << "_buffer_;\n";
1749}

1751string CodeGen_C::print_expr(const Expr &e) {
1752 id = "$$ BAD ID $$";
1753 e.accept(this);
1754 return id;
1755}

1757string CodeGen_C::print_cast_expr(const Type &t, const Expr &e) {
1758 string value = print_expr(e);
1759 string type = print_type(t);
1760 if (t.is_vector() &&
1761 t.lanes() == e.type().lanes() &&
1762 t != e.type()) {
1763 return print_assignment(t, type + "_ops::convert_from<" + print_type(e.type()) + ">(" + value + ")");
1764 } else {
1765 return print_assignment(t, "(" + type + ")(" + value + ")");
1766 }
1767}

1769void CodeGen_C::print_stmt(const Stmt &s) {
1770 s.accept(this);
1771}
1772
1773string CodeGen_C::print_assignment(Type t, const std::string &rhs) {
1774 auto cached = cache.find(rhs);
1775 if (cached == cache.end()) {
1776 id = unique_name('_');
1777 const char *const_flag = output_kind == CPlusPlusImplementation ? "const " : "";
1778 stream << get_indent() << print_type(t, AppendSpace) << const_flag << id << " = " << rhs << ";\n";
1779 cache[rhs] = id;
1780 } else {
1781 id = cached->second;
1782 }
1783 return id;
1784}

1800 stream << "}\n";

1829
1830void CodeGen_C::visit(const Div *op) {
1831 int bits;
1832 if (is_const_power_of_two_integer(op->b, &bits)) {
1833 visit_binop(op->type, op->a, make_const(op->a.type(), bits), ">>");
1834 } else if (op->type.is_int()) {
1835 print_expr(lower_euclidean_div(op->a, op->b));
1836 } else {
1837 visit_binop(op->type, op->a, op->b, "/");
1838 }
1839}
1840
1841void CodeGen_C::visit(const Mod *op) {
1842 int bits;
1843 if (is_const_power_of_two_integer(op->b, &bits)) {
1844 visit_binop(op->type, op->a, make_const(op->a.type(), (1 << bits) - 1), "&");
1845 } else if (op->type.is_int()) {
1846 print_expr(lower_euclidean_mod(op->a, op->b));
1847 } else if (op->type.is_float()) {
1848 string arg0 = print_expr(op->a);
1849 string arg1 = print_expr(op->b);
1850 ostringstream rhs;
1851 rhs << "fmod(" << arg0 << ", " << arg1 << ")";
1852 print_assignment(op->type, rhs.str());
1853 } else {
1854 visit_binop(op->type, op->a, op->b, "%");
1855 }
1856}

1957// NaN is the only float/double for which this is true... and
1958// surprisingly, there doesn't seem to be a portable isnan function
1959// (dsharlet).
1960template<typename T>
1961static bool isnan(T x) {
1962 return x != x;
1963}
1964
1965template<typename T>
1966static bool isinf(T x) {
1967 return std::numeric_limits<T>::has_infinity && (x == std::numeric_limits<T>::infinity() ||
1968 x == -std::numeric_limits<T>::infinity());
1969}
1970
1971void CodeGen_C::visit(const FloatImm *op) {
1972 if (isnan(op->value)) {
1973 id = "nan_f32()";
1974 } else if (isinf(op->value)) {
1975 if (op->value > 0) {
1976 id = "inf_f32()";
1977 } else {
1978 id = "neg_inf_f32()";
1979 }
1980 } else {
1981 // Write the constant as reinterpreted uint to avoid any bits lost in conversion.
1982 union {
1983 uint32_t as_uint;
1984 float as_float;
1985 } u;
1986 u.as_float = op->value;
1987
1988 ostringstream oss;
1989 if (op->type.bits() == 64) {
1990 oss << "(double) ";
1991 }
1992 oss << "float_from_bits(" << u.as_uint << " /* " << u.as_float << " */)";
1993 print_assignment(op->type, oss.str());
1994 }
1995}
1996
1997void CodeGen_C::visit(const Call *op) {
1998
1999 internal_assert(op->is_extern() || op->is_intrinsic())
2000 << "Can only codegen extern calls and intrinsics\n";
2001
2002 ostringstream rhs;
2003
2004 // Handle intrinsics first
2005 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::debug_to_file)) {
2006 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3);
2007 const StringImm *string_imm = op->args[0].as<StringImm>();
2008 internal_assert(string_imm);
2009 string filename = string_imm->value;
2010 string typecode = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2011 string buffer = print_name(print_expr(op->args[2]));
2012
2013 rhs << "halide_debug_to_file(_ucon, "
2014 << "\"" << filename << "\", "
2015 << typecode
2016 << ", (struct halide_buffer_t *)" << buffer << ")";
2017 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_and)) {
2018 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
2019 string a0 = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2020 string a1 = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2021 rhs << a0 << " & " << a1;
2022 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_xor)) {
2023 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
2024 string a0 = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2025 string a1 = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2026 rhs << a0 << " ^ " << a1;
2027 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_or)) {
2028 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
2029 string a0 = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2030 string a1 = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2031 rhs << a0 << " | " << a1;
2032 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_not)) {
2033 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 1);
2034 rhs << "~" << print_expr(op->args[0]);
2035 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::reinterpret)) {
2036 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 1);
2037 rhs << print_reinterpret(op->type, op->args[0]);
2038 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_left)) {
2039 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
2040 string a0 = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2041 string a1 = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2042 rhs << a0 << " << " << a1;
2043 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_right)) {
2044 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
2045 string a0 = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2046 string a1 = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2047 rhs << a0 << " >> " << a1;
2048 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::count_leading_zeros) ||
2049 op->is_intrinsic(Call::count_trailing_zeros) ||
2050 op->is_intrinsic(Call::popcount)) {
2051 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 1);
2052 if (op->args[0].type().is_vector()) {
2053 rhs << print_scalarized_expr(op);
2054 } else {
2055 string a0 = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2056 rhs << "halide_" << op->name << "(" << a0 << ")";
2057 }
2058 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::lerp)) {
2059 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3);
2060 Expr e = lower_lerp(op->args[0], op->args[1], op->args[2]);
2061 rhs << print_expr(e);
2062 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::absd)) {
2063 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
2064 Expr a = op->args[0];
2065 Expr b = op->args[1];
2066 Expr e = cast(op->type, select(a < b, b - a, a - b));
2067 rhs << print_expr(e);
2068 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::return_second)) {
2069 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
2070 string arg0 = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2071 string arg1 = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2072 rhs << "return_second(" << arg0 << ", " << arg1 << ")";
2073 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::if_then_else)) {
2074 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3);
2075
2076 string result_id = unique_name('_');
2077
2078 stream << get_indent() << print_type(op->args[1].type(), AppendSpace)
2079 << result_id << ";\n";
2080
2081 string cond_id = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2082
2083 stream << get_indent() << "if (" << cond_id << ")\n";
2084 open_scope();
2085 string true_case = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2086 stream << get_indent() << result_id << " = " << true_case << ";\n";
2087 close_scope("if " + cond_id);
2088 stream << get_indent() << "else\n";
2089 open_scope();
2090 string false_case = print_expr(op->args[2]);
2091 stream << get_indent() << result_id << " = " << false_case << ";\n";
2092 close_scope("if " + cond_id + " else");
2093
2094 rhs << result_id;
2095 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::require)) {
2096 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3);
2097 if (op->args[0].type().is_vector()) {
2098 rhs << print_scalarized_expr(op);
2099 } else {
2100 create_assertion(op->args[0], op->args[2]);
2101 rhs << print_expr(op->args[1]);
2102 }
2103 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::abs)) {
2104 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 1);
2105 Expr a0 = op->args[0];
2106 rhs << print_expr(cast(op->type, select(a0 > 0, a0, -a0)));
2107 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::memoize_expr)) {
2108 internal_assert(!op->args.empty());
2109 string arg = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2110 rhs << "(" << arg << ")";
2111 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::alloca)) {
2112 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 1);
2113 internal_assert(op->type.is_handle());
2114 if (op->type == type_of<struct halide_buffer_t *>() &&
2115 Call::as_intrinsic(op->args[0], {Call::size_of_halide_buffer_t})) {
2116 stream << get_indent();
2117 string buf_name = unique_name('b');
2118 stream << "halide_buffer_t " << buf_name << ";\n";
2119 rhs << "&" << buf_name;
2120 } else {
2121 // Make a stack of uint64_ts
2122 string size = print_expr(simplify((op->args[0] + 7) / 8));
2123 stream << get_indent();
2124 string array_name = unique_name('a');
2125 stream << "uint64_t " << array_name << "[" << size << "];";
2126 rhs << "(" << print_type(op->type) << ")(&" << array_name << ")";
2127 }
2128 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::make_struct)) {
2129 if (op->args.empty()) {
2130 internal_assert(op->type.handle_type);
2131 // Add explicit cast so that different structs can't cache to the same value
2132 rhs << "(" << print_type(op->type) << ")(NULL)";
2133 } else if (op->type == type_of<halide_dimension_t *>()) {
2134 // Emit a shape
2135
2136 // Get the args
2137 vector<string> values;
2138 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
2139 values.push_back(print_expr(op->args[i]));
2140 }
2141
2142 static_assert(sizeof(halide_dimension_t) == 4 * sizeof(int32_t),
2143 "CodeGen_C assumes a halide_dimension_t is four densely-packed int32_ts");
2144
2145 internal_assert(values.size() % 4 == 0);
2146 int dimension = values.size() / 4;
2147
2148 string shape_name = unique_name('s');
2149 stream
2150 << get_indent() << "struct halide_dimension_t " << shape_name
2151 << "[" << dimension << "] = {\n";
2152 indent++;
2153 for (int i = 0; i < dimension; i++) {
2154 stream
2155 << get_indent() << "{"
2156 << values[i * 4 + 0] << ", "
2157 << values[i * 4 + 1] << ", "
2158 << values[i * 4 + 2] << ", "
2159 << values[i * 4 + 3] << "},\n";
2160 }
2161 indent--;
2162 stream << get_indent() << "};\n";
2163
2164 rhs << shape_name;
2165 } else {
2166 // Emit a declaration like:
2167 // struct {const int f_0, const char f_1, const int f_2} foo = {3, 'c', 4};
2168
2169 // Get the args
2170 vector<string> values;
2171 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
2172 values.push_back(print_expr(op->args[i]));
2173 }
2174 stream << get_indent() << "struct {\n";
2175 // List the types.
2176 indent++;
2177 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
2178 stream << get_indent() << "const " << print_type(op->args[i].type()) << " f_" << i << ";\n";
2179 }
2180 indent--;
2181 string struct_name = unique_name('s');
2182 stream << get_indent() << "} " << struct_name << " = {\n";
2183 // List the values.
2184 indent++;
2185 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
2186 stream << get_indent() << values[i];
2187 if (i < op->args.size() - 1) {
2188 stream << ",";
2189 }
2190 stream << "\n";
2191 }
2192 indent--;
2193 stream << get_indent() << "};\n";
2194
2195 // Return a pointer to it of the appropriate type
2196
2197 // TODO: This is dubious type-punning. We really need to
2198 // find a better way to do this. We dodge the problem for
2199 // the specific case of buffer shapes in the case above.
2200 if (op->type.handle_type) {
2201 rhs << "(" << print_type(op->type) << ")";
2202 }
2203 rhs << "(&" << struct_name << ")";
2204 }
2205 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::stringify)) {
2206 // Rewrite to an snprintf
2207 vector<string> printf_args;
2208 string format_string = "";
2209 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
2210 Type t = op->args[i].type();
2211 printf_args.push_back(print_expr(op->args[i]));
2212 if (t.is_int()) {
2213 format_string += "%lld";
2214 printf_args[i] = "(long long)(" + printf_args[i] + ")";
2215 } else if (t.is_uint()) {
2216 format_string += "%llu";
2217 printf_args[i] = "(long long unsigned)(" + printf_args[i] + ")";
2218 } else if (t.is_float()) {
2219 if (t.bits() == 32) {
2220 format_string += "%f";
2221 } else {
2222 format_string += "%e";
2223 }
2224 } else if (op->args[i].as<StringImm>()) {
2225 format_string += "%s";
2226 } else {
2227 internal_assert(t.is_handle());
2228 format_string += "%p";
2229 }
2230 }
2231 string buf_name = unique_name('b');
2232 stream << get_indent() << "char " << buf_name << "[1024];\n";
2233 stream << get_indent() << "snprintf(" << buf_name << ", 1024, \"" << format_string << "\", " << with_commas(printf_args) << ");\n";
2234 rhs << buf_name;
2235
2236 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::register_destructor)) {
2237 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
2238 const StringImm *fn = op->args[0].as<StringImm>();
2239 internal_assert(fn);
2240 string arg = print_expr(op->args[1]);
2241
2242 stream << get_indent();
2243 // Make a struct on the stack that calls the given function as a destructor
2244 string struct_name = unique_name('s');
2245 string instance_name = unique_name('d');
2246 stream << "struct " << struct_name << " { "
2247 << "void * const ucon; "
2248 << "void * const arg; "
2249 << "" << struct_name << "(void *ucon, void *a) : ucon(ucon), arg((void *)a) {} "
2250 << "~" << struct_name << "() { " << fn->value + "(ucon, arg); } "
2251 << "} " << instance_name << "(_ucon, " << arg << ");\n";
2252 rhs << print_expr(0);
2253 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::div_round_to_zero)) {
2254 rhs << print_expr(op->args[0]) << " / " << print_expr(op->args[1]);
2255 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::mod_round_to_zero)) {
2256 rhs << print_expr(op->args[0]) << " % " << print_expr(op->args[1]);
2257 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::mux)) {
2258 rhs << print_expr(lower_mux(op));
2259 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::signed_integer_overflow)) {
2260 user_error << "Signed integer overflow occurred during constant-folding. Signed"
2261 " integer overflow for int32 and int64 is undefined behavior in"
2262 " Halide.\n";
2263 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::prefetch)) {
2264 user_assert((op->args.size() == 4) && is_const_one(op->args[2]))
2265 << "Only prefetch of 1 cache line is supported in C backend.\n";
2266 const Variable *base = op->args[0].as<Variable>();
2267 internal_assert(base && base->type.is_handle());
2268 rhs << "__builtin_prefetch("
2269 << "((" << print_type(op->type) << " *)" << print_name(base->name)
2270 << " + " << print_expr(op->args[1]) << "), 1)";
2271 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::size_of_halide_buffer_t)) {
2272 rhs << "(sizeof(halide_buffer_t))";
2273 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::strict_float)) {
2274 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 1);
2275 string arg0 = print_expr(op->args[0]);
2276 rhs << "(" << arg0 << ")";
2277 } else if (op->is_intrinsic()) {
2278 Expr lowered = lower_intrinsic(op);
2279 if (lowered.defined()) {
2280 rhs << print_expr(lowered);
2281 } else {
2282 // TODO: other intrinsics
2283 internal_error << "Unhandled intrinsic in C backend: " << op->name << "\n";
2284 }
2285 } else {
2286 // Generic extern calls
2287 rhs << print_extern_call(op);
2288 }
2289
2290 // Special-case halide_print, which has IR that returns int, but really return void.
2291 // The clean thing to do would be to change the definition of halide_print() to return
2292 // an ignored int, but as halide_print() has many overrides downstream (and in third-party
2293 // consumers), this is arguably a simpler fix for allowing halide_print() to work in the C++ backend.
2294 if (op->name == "halide_print") {
2295 stream << get_indent() << rhs.str() << ";\n";
2296 // Make an innocuous assignment value for our caller (probably an Evaluate node) to ignore.
2297 print_assignment(op->type, "0");
2298 } else {
2299 print_assignment(op->type, rhs.str());
2300 }
2301}
2302
2303string CodeGen_C::print_scalarized_expr(const Expr &e) {
2304 Type t = e.type();
2305 internal_assert(t.is_vector());
2306 string v = unique_name('_');
2307 stream << get_indent() << print_type(t, AppendSpace) << v << ";\n";
2308 for (int lane = 0; lane < t.lanes(); lane++) {
2309 Expr e2 = extract_lane(e, lane);
2310 string elem = print_expr(e2);
2311 ostringstream rhs;
2312 rhs << print_type(t) + "_ops::replace(" << v << ", " << lane << ", " << elem << ")";
2313 v = print_assignment(t, rhs.str());
2314 }
2315 return v;
2316}
2317
2318string CodeGen_C::print_extern_call(const Call *op) {
2319 if (op->type.is_vector()) {
2320 // Need to split into multiple scalar calls.
2321 return print_scalarized_expr(op);
2322 }
2323 ostringstream rhs;
2324 vector<string> args(op->args.size());
2325 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
2326 args[i] = print_expr(op->args[i]);
2327 // This substitution ensures const correctness for all calls
2328 if (args[i] == "__user_context") {
2329 args[i] = "_ucon";
2330 }
2331 }
2332 if (function_takes_user_context(op->name)) {
2333 args.insert(args.begin(), "_ucon");
2334 }
2335 rhs << op->name << "(" << with_commas(args) << ")";
2336 return rhs.str();
2337}
2338
2339void CodeGen_C::visit(const Load *op) {
2340 // TODO: We could replicate the logic in the llvm codegen which decides whether
2341 // the vector access can be aligned. Doing so would also require introducing
2342 // aligned type equivalents for all the vector types.
2343 ostringstream rhs;
2344
2345 Type t = op->type;
2346 string name = print_name(op->name);
2347
2348 // If we're loading a contiguous ramp into a vector, just load the vector
2349 Expr dense_ramp_base = strided_ramp_base(op->index, 1);
2350 if (dense_ramp_base.defined() && is_const_one(op->predicate)) {
2351 internal_assert(t.is_vector());
2352 string id_ramp_base = print_expr(dense_ramp_base);
2353 rhs << print_type(t) + "_ops::load(" << name << ", " << id_ramp_base << ")";
2354 } else if (op->index.type().is_vector()) {
2355 // If index is a vector, gather vector elements.
2356 internal_assert(t.is_vector());
2357 string id_index = print_expr(op->index);
2358 if (is_const_one(op->predicate)) {
2359 rhs << print_type(t) + "_ops::load_gather(" << name << ", " << id_index << ")";
2360 } else {
2361 string id_predicate = print_expr(op->predicate);
2362 rhs << print_type(t) + "_ops::load_predicated(" << name << ", " << id_index << ", " << id_predicate << ")";
2363 }
2364 } else {
2365 user_assert(is_const_one(op->predicate)) << "Predicated scalar load is not supported by C backend.\n";
2366
2367 string id_index = print_expr(op->index);
2368 bool type_cast_needed = !(allocations.contains(op->name) &&
2369 allocations.get(op->name).type.element_of() == t.element_of());
2370 if (type_cast_needed) {
2371 const char *const_flag = output_kind == CPlusPlusImplementation ? "const " : "";
2372 rhs << "((" << const_flag << print_type(t.element_of()) << " *)" << name << ")";
2373 } else {
2374 rhs << name;
2375 }
2376 rhs << "[" << id_index << "]";
2377 }
2378 print_assignment(t, rhs.str());
2379}
2380
2381void CodeGen_C::visit(const Store *op) {
2382 Type t = op->value.type();
2383
2384 if (inside_atomic_mutex_node) {
2385 user_assert(t.is_scalar())
2386 << "The vectorized atomic operation for the store" << op->name
2387 << " is lowered into a mutex lock, which does not support vectorization.\n";
2388 }
2389
2390 // Issue atomic store if we are in the designated producer.
2391 if (emit_atomic_stores) {
2392 stream << "#if defined(_OPENMP)\n";
2393 stream << "#pragma omp atomic\n";
2394 stream << "#else\n";
2395 stream << "#error \"Atomic stores in the C backend are only supported in compilers that support OpenMP.\"\n";
2396 stream << "#endif\n";
2397 }
2398
2399 string id_value = print_expr(op->value);
2400 string name = print_name(op->name);
2401
2402 // TODO: We could replicate the logic in the llvm codegen which decides whether
2403 // the vector access can be aligned. Doing so would also require introducing
2404 // aligned type equivalents for all the vector types.
2405
2406 // If we're writing a contiguous ramp, just store the vector.
2407 Expr dense_ramp_base = strided_ramp_base(op->index, 1);
2408 if (dense_ramp_base.defined() && is_const_one(op->predicate)) {
2409 internal_assert(op->value.type().is_vector());
2410 string id_ramp_base = print_expr(dense_ramp_base);
2411 stream << get_indent() << print_type(t) + "_ops::store(" << id_value << ", " << name << ", " << id_ramp_base << ");\n";
2412 } else if (op->index.type().is_vector()) {
2413 // If index is a vector, scatter vector elements.
2414 internal_assert(t.is_vector());
2415 string id_index = print_expr(op->index);
2416 if (is_const_one(op->predicate)) {
2417 stream << get_indent() << print_type(t) + "_ops::store_scatter(" << id_value << ", " << name << ", " << id_index << ");\n";
2418 } else {
2419 string id_predicate = print_expr(op->predicate);
2420 stream << get_indent() << print_type(t) + "_ops::store_predicated(" << id_value << ", " << name << ", " << id_index << ", " << id_predicate << ");\n";
2421 }
2422 } else {
2423 user_assert(is_const_one(op->predicate)) << "Predicated scalar store is not supported by C backend.\n";
2424
2425 bool type_cast_needed =
2426 t.is_handle() ||
2427 !allocations.contains(op->name) ||
2428 allocations.get(op->name).type != t;
2429
2430 string id_index = print_expr(op->index);
2431 stream << get_indent();
2432 if (type_cast_needed) {
2433 stream << "((" << print_type(t) << " *)" << name << ")";
2434 } else {
2435 stream << name;
2436 }
2437 stream << "[" << id_index << "] = " << id_value << ";\n";
2438 }
2439 cache.clear();
2440}

2442void CodeGen_C::visit(const Let *op) {
2443 string id_value = print_expr(op->value);
2444 Expr body = op->body;
2445 if (op->value.type().is_handle()) {
2446 // The body might contain a Load that references this directly
2447 // by name, so we can't rewrite the name.
2448 stream << get_indent() << print_type(op->value.type())
2449 << " " << print_name(op->name)
2450 << " = " << id_value << ";\n";
2451 } else {
2452 Expr new_var = Variable::make(op->value.type(), id_value);
2453 body = substitute(op->name, new_var, body);
2454 }

2458void CodeGen_C::visit(const Select *op) {
2459 ostringstream rhs;
2460 string type = print_type(op->type);
2461 string true_val = print_expr(op->true_value);
2462 string false_val = print_expr(op->false_value);
2463 string cond = print_expr(op->condition);
2464
2465 // clang doesn't support the ternary operator on OpenCL style vectors.
2466 // See: https://bugs.llvm.org/show_bug.cgi?id=33103
2467 if (op->condition.type().is_scalar()) {
2468 rhs << "(" << type << ")"
2469 << "(" << cond
2470 << " ? " << true_val
2471 << " : " << false_val
2472 << ")";
2473 } else {
2474 rhs << type << "_ops::select(" << cond << ", " << true_val << ", " << false_val << ")";
2475 }
2476 print_assignment(op->type, rhs.str());
2477}

2479Expr CodeGen_C::scalarize_vector_reduce(const VectorReduce *op) {
2480 Expr (*binop)(Expr, Expr) = nullptr;
2481 switch (op->op) {
2482 case VectorReduce::Add:
2483 binop = Add::make;
2484 break;
2485 case VectorReduce::Mul:
2486 binop = Mul::make;
2487 break;
2488 case VectorReduce::Min:
2489 binop = Min::make;
2490 break;
2491 case VectorReduce::Max:
2492 binop = Max::make;
2493 break;
2494 case VectorReduce::And:
2495 binop = And::make;
2496 break;
2497 case VectorReduce::Or:
2498 binop = Or::make;
2499 break;
2500 case VectorReduce::SaturatingAdd:
2501 binop = saturating_add;
2502 break;
2503 }
2504
2505 std::vector<Expr> lanes;
2506 int outer_lanes = op->type.lanes();
2507 int inner_lanes = op->value.type().lanes() / outer_lanes;
2508 for (int outer = 0; outer < outer_lanes; outer++) {
2509 Expr reduction = extract_lane(op->value, outer * inner_lanes);
2510 for (int inner = 1; inner < inner_lanes; inner++) {
2511 reduction = binop(reduction, extract_lane(op->value, outer * inner_lanes + inner));
2512 }
2513 lanes.push_back(reduction);
2514 }
2515
2516 // No need to concat if there is only a single value.
2517 if (lanes.size() == 1) {
2518 return lanes[0];
2519 }
2520
2521 return Shuffle::make_concat(lanes);
2522}

2531 print_assignment(op->type, print_scalarized_expr(scalarized));

2551// Halide asserts have different semantics to C asserts. They're
2552// supposed to clean up and make the containing function return
2553// -1, so we can't use the C version of assert. Instead we convert
2554// to an if statement.
2555void CodeGen_C::create_assertion(const string &id_cond, const Expr &message) {
2556 internal_assert(!message.defined() || message.type() == Int(32))
2557 << "Assertion result is not an int: " << message;
2558
2559 if (target.has_feature(Target::NoAsserts)) {
2560 stream << get_indent() << "halide_unused(" << id_cond << ");\n";
2561 return;
2562 }
2563
2564 stream << get_indent() << "if (!" << id_cond << ")\n";
2565 open_scope();
2566 string id_msg = print_expr(message);
2567 stream << get_indent() << "return " << id_msg << ";\n";
2568 close_scope("");
2569}

2684void CodeGen_C::visit(const Allocate *op) {
2685 open_scope();
2686
2687 string op_name = print_name(op->name);
2688 string op_type = print_type(op->type, AppendSpace);
2689
2690 // For sizes less than 8k, do a stack allocation
2691 bool on_stack = false;
2692 int32_t constant_size;
2693 string size_id;
2694 Type size_id_type;
2695
2696 if (op->new_expr.defined()) {
2697 Allocation alloc;
2698 alloc.type = op->type;
2699 allocations.push(op->name, alloc);
2700 heap_allocations.push(op->name);
2701 string new_e = print_expr(op->new_expr);
2702 stream << get_indent() << op_type << " *" << op_name << " = (" << op_type << "*)" << new_e << ";\n";
2703 } else {
2704 constant_size = op->constant_allocation_size();
2705 if (constant_size > 0) {
2706 int64_t stack_bytes = (int64_t)constant_size * op->type.bytes();
2707
2708 if (stack_bytes > ((int64_t(1) << 31) - 1)) {
2709 user_error << "Total size for allocation "
2710 << op->name << " is constant but exceeds 2^31 - 1.\n";
2711 } else {
2712 size_id_type = Int(32);
2713 size_id = print_expr(make_const(size_id_type, constant_size));
2714
2715 if (op->memory_type == MemoryType::Stack ||
2716 op->memory_type == MemoryType::Register ||
2717 (op->memory_type == MemoryType::Auto &&
2718 can_allocation_fit_on_stack(stack_bytes))) {
2719 on_stack = true;
2720 }
2721 }
2722 } else {
2723 // Check that the allocation is not scalar (if it were scalar
2724 // it would have constant size).
2725 internal_assert(!op->extents.empty());
2726
2727 size_id = print_assignment(Int(64), print_expr(op->extents[0]));
2728 size_id_type = Int(64);
2729
2730 for (size_t i = 1; i < op->extents.size(); i++) {
2731 // Make the code a little less cluttered for two-dimensional case
2732 string new_size_id_rhs;
2733 string next_extent = print_expr(op->extents[i]);
2734 if (i > 1) {
2735 new_size_id_rhs = "(" + size_id + " > ((int64_t(1) << 31) - 1)) ? " + size_id + " : (" + size_id + " * " + next_extent + ")";
2736 } else {
2737 new_size_id_rhs = size_id + " * " + next_extent;
2738 }
2739 size_id = print_assignment(Int(64), new_size_id_rhs);
2740 }
2741 stream << get_indent() << "if (("
2742 << size_id << " > ((int64_t(1) << 31) - 1)) || (("
2743 << size_id << " * sizeof("
2744 << op_type << ")) > ((int64_t(1) << 31) - 1)))\n";
2745 open_scope();
2746 stream << get_indent();
2747 // TODO: call halide_error_buffer_allocation_too_large() here instead
2748 // TODO: call create_assertion() so that NoAssertions works
2749 stream << "halide_error(_ucon, "
2750 << "\"32-bit signed overflow computing size of allocation " << op->name << "\\n\");\n";
2751 stream << get_indent() << "return -1;\n";
2752 close_scope("overflow test " + op->name);
2753 }
2754
2755 // Check the condition to see if this allocation should actually be created.
2756 // If the allocation is on the stack, the only condition we can respect is
2757 // unconditional false (otherwise a non-constant-sized array declaration
2758 // will be generated).
2759 if (!on_stack || is_const_zero(op->condition)) {
2760 Expr conditional_size = Select::make(op->condition,
2761 Variable::make(size_id_type, size_id),
2762 make_const(size_id_type, 0));
2763 conditional_size = simplify(conditional_size);
2764 size_id = print_assignment(Int(64), print_expr(conditional_size));
2765 }
2766
2767 Allocation alloc;
2768 alloc.type = op->type;
2769 allocations.push(op->name, alloc);
2770
2771 stream << get_indent() << op_type;
2772
2773 if (on_stack) {
2774 stream << op_name
2775 << "[" << size_id << "];\n";
2776 } else {
2777 stream << "*"
2778 << op_name
2779 << " = ("
2780 << op_type
2781 << " *)halide_malloc(_ucon, sizeof("
2782 << op_type
2783 << ")*" << size_id << ");\n";
2784 heap_allocations.push(op->name);
2785 }
2786 }
2787
2788 if (!on_stack) {
2789 create_assertion(op_name, Call::make(Int(32), "halide_error_out_of_memory", {}, Call::Extern));
2790
2791 stream << get_indent();
2792 string free_function = op->free_function.empty() ? "halide_free" : op->free_function;
2793 stream << "HalideFreeHelper " << op_name << "_free(_ucon, "
2794 << op_name << ", " << free_function << ");\n";
2795 }
2796
2797 op->body.accept(this);
2798
2799 // Free the memory if it was allocated on the heap and there is no matching
2800 // Free node.
2801 print_heap_free(op->name);
2802 if (allocations.contains(op->name)) {
2803 allocations.pop(op->name);
2804 }
2805
2806 close_scope("alloc " + print_name(op->name));
2807}

2812 heap_allocations.pop(alloc_name);

2853void CodeGen_C::visit(const Shuffle *op) {
2854 internal_assert(!op->vectors.empty());
2855 for (size_t i = 1; i < op->vectors.size(); i++) {
2856 internal_assert(op->vectors[0].type() == op->vectors[i].type());
2857 }
2858 internal_assert(op->type.lanes() == (int)op->indices.size());
2859 const int max_index = (int)(op->vectors[0].type().lanes() * op->vectors.size());
2860 for (int i : op->indices) {
2861 internal_assert(i >= -1 && i < max_index);
2862 }
2863
2864 std::vector<string> vecs;
2865 for (const Expr &v : op->vectors) {
2866 vecs.push_back(print_expr(v));
2867 }
2868 ostringstream rhs;
2869 if (op->type.is_scalar()) {
2870 // Deduce which vector we need. Apparently it's not required
2871 // that all vectors have identical lanes, so a loop is required.
2872 // Since idx of -1 means "don't care", we'll treat it as 0 to simplify.
2873 int idx = std::max(0, op->indices[0]);
2874 for (size_t vec_idx = 0; vec_idx < op->vectors.size(); vec_idx++) {
2875 const int vec_lanes = op->vectors[vec_idx].type().lanes();
2876 if (idx < vec_lanes) {
2877 rhs << vecs[vec_idx];
2878 if (op->vectors[vec_idx].type().is_vector()) {
2879 rhs << "[" << idx << "]";
2880 }
2881 break;
2882 }
2883 idx -= vec_lanes;
2884 }
2885 internal_assert(!rhs.str().empty());
2886 } else {
2887 internal_assert(op->vectors[0].type().is_vector());
2888 string src = vecs[0];
2889 if (op->vectors.size() > 1) {
2890 // This code has always assumed/required that all the vectors
2891 // have identical types, so let's verify
2892 const Type t0 = op->vectors[0].type();
2893 for (const auto &v : op->vectors) {
2894 internal_assert(t0 == v.type());
2895 }
2896 ostringstream rhs;
2897 string storage_name = unique_name('_');
2898 // Combine them into one vector. Clang emits excellent code via this
2899 // union approach (typically without going thru memory) for both x64 and arm64.
2900 stream << get_indent() << "union { "
2901 << print_type(t0) << " src[" << vecs.size() << "]; "
2902 << print_type(op->type) << " dst; } "
2903 << storage_name << " = {{ " << with_commas(vecs) << " }};\n";
2904 src = storage_name + ".dst";
2905 }
2906 rhs << print_type(op->type) << "_ops::shuffle<" << with_commas(op->indices) << ">(" << src << ")";
2907 }
2908 print_assignment(op->type, rhs.str());
2909}

2911void CodeGen_C::test() {
2912 LoweredArgument buffer_arg("buf", Argument::OutputBuffer, Int(32), 3, ArgumentEstimates{});
2913 LoweredArgument float_arg("alpha", Argument::InputScalar, Float(32), 0, ArgumentEstimates{});
2914 LoweredArgument int_arg("beta", Argument::InputScalar, Int(32), 0, ArgumentEstimates{});

2919 Param<int> beta("beta");

2922 s = LetStmt::make("x", beta + 1, s);

2925 s = Allocate::make("tmp.heap", Int(32), MemoryType::Heap, {43, beta}, const_true(), s);

2928

2930 m.append(LoweredFunc("test1", args, s, LinkageType::External));
2931
2932 ostringstream source;
2933 ostringstream macros;
2934 {
2935 CodeGen_C cg(source, Target("host"), CodeGen_C::CImplementation);
2936 cg.compile(m);
2937 }

2939 string src = source.str();
2940 string correct_source =
2941 headers +
2942 globals +
2943 string((const char *)halide_internal_runtime_header_HalideRuntime_h) + '\n' +
2944 string((const char *)halide_internal_initmod_inlined_c) + '\n' +
2945 macros.str() + '\n' + kDefineMustUseResult + R"GOLDEN_CODE(
2946#ifndef HALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS
2947#define HALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS
2948#endif
2949
2950
2951
2952#ifdef __cplusplus
2953extern "C" {
2954#endif

2956HALIDE_FUNCTION_ATTRS
2957int test1(struct halide_buffer_t *_buf_buffer, float _alpha, int32_t _beta, void const *__user_context) {
2958 void * const _ucon = const_cast<void *>(__user_context);
2959 void *_0 = _halide_buffer_get_host(_buf_buffer);
2960 void * _buf = _0;
2961 {
2962 int64_t _1 = 43;
2963 int64_t _2 = _1 * _beta;
2964 if ((_2 > ((int64_t(1) << 31) - 1)) || ((_2 * sizeof(int32_t )) > ((int64_t(1) << 31) - 1)))
2965 {
2966 halide_error(_ucon, "32-bit signed overflow computing size of allocation tmp.heap\n");
2967 return -1;
2968 } // overflow test tmp.heap
2969 int64_t _3 = _2;
2970 int32_t *_tmp_heap = (int32_t *)halide_malloc(_ucon, sizeof(int32_t )*_3);
2971 if (!_tmp_heap)
2972 {
2973 int32_t _4 = halide_error_out_of_memory(_ucon);
2974 return _4;
2975 }
2976 HalideFreeHelper _tmp_heap_free(_ucon, _tmp_heap, halide_free);
2977 {
2978 int32_t _tmp_stack[127];
2979 int32_t _5 = _beta + 1;
2980 int32_t _6;
2981 bool _7 = _5 < 1;
2982 if (_7)
2983 {
